<Base title="About — Jesus Garcia" description="About Jesus Garcia — engineering, AI, and building things that work.">
  <section class="page-section">
    <h1 class="page-section-title page-section-title--about">About</h1>
    <article class="prose">
      <p>
        Based in Belgium, originally from Spain.
      </p>
      <p>
        My career has been a bit all over the place. Industrial engineering in Spain, a master's
        in AI in Belgium, then almost four years of neuroscience research at <a href="https://www.kuleuven.be/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">KU Leuven</a> trying to understand the
        neurosignatures of attention in the human brain. I've always been fascinated by
        intelligence, and I kept following that thread wherever it went.
      </p>
      <p>
        Turns out what I really like is getting stuff done. So engineering was the way to go.
      </p>
      <p>
        Currently I work as a data and platform engineer at <a href="https://www.dataminded.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Dataminded</a>, a consultancy. My work sits at the intersection of AI,
        data, and platform. What I love is enabling other people, building tools so that scientists
        can do their job without worrying about the engineering. AI systems and agents are a super
        good way to do that, and I really believe in them.
      </p>
      <p>
        But the clients I work with are big enterprises. It's not just "deploy an agent locally and run it." It takes
        proper engineering, talking to people, iterating back and forth, scalability, system design.
        These kind of things are what I want to talk about. Beyond the hype, what it really takes to
        build these systems properly.
      </p>
      <h2>Technologies</h2>
      <p>
        Python is my main language. For AI, I use Agno for agent orchestration, MLflow for
        traditional ML, and I get my models from Hugging Face. I like open source.
      </p>
      <p>
        On the platform side, FastAPI for APIs, Docker for containerization, Terraform for
        infrastructure as code, and Azure is where I spend most of my cloud time.
      </p>
      <p>
        I've also been playing around a lot with coding harnesses. Cursor, Claude Code, Codex,
        you name it. I've tried them all.
      </p>

      <h2>What I write about</h2>
      <p>
        The architecture decisions, the debugging stories, the things that look simple in a diagram
        but take six months to get right.
      </p>
      <p>
        These posts start as talks and presentations. I speak, transcribe, and then edit, so the
        writing sounds like me. Not like a press release. And to be fair, I might write about
        random stuff too. Who knows.
      </p>

      <h2>Outside of work</h2>
      <p>
        I like movies that make me think. The kind where not a lot seems to happen, but you're
        still thinking about them days after. One of my favorites is The Four Hundred Blows.
      </p>
      <p>
        I also really like dancing. I probably suck at it, but it's kind of a meditation for me.
      </p>

      <p>
        You can find me on <a href="https://github.com/jesgarram" target="_blank" rel="noopener">GitHub</a> and <a href="https://linkedin.com/in/jesusgarciaramirez" target="_blank" rel="noopener">LinkedIn</a>.
      </p>
    </article>
  </section>
</Base>
